        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName><hi rend="underline">St. Louis</hi></placeName>. A correspondent from this flourishing<lb/> city writes as follows</p>
			<p><placeName>St Louis&#44; Mo</placeName>&#44; <date>May 4th 5611</date>.</p>
			<p><addressee>Mr Isaac Leeser</addressee> <placeName>Ph<hi rend="sup">a</hi></placeName></p>
			<p>With sincere joy and an admiration&#44; as only my own experi<lb/>ences&#44; earned on your thorufull<add>&#63;</add> field&#44; can inspire&#44; I received the<lb/> first number of the new series of your Occident&#44; and I determi&#45;<lb/>ned to obey your friendly and repeated demand for some con<lb/>tributions of my pen. To save you the trouble of translating&#45;<lb/> I write <del>you</del> in English and hope&#44; your readers will excuse<lb/> their German brother for the want of elegance and even<lb/> correctness of style&#44; and <del>might anyhow</del> that they may find <del>the manner</del> what he<lb/> offers them&#44; worthy of their noticing.</p>
			<p>As a correspondent <add>at</add> of this place I feel it my duty to begin<lb/> with local matters&#44; though they may not be of much interest&#44; as<lb/> <del>far as I know of them&#44; which&#44; I confess</del> my knowledge of them is but very little and <del>yet less</del> tho<add>&#63;</add> not<lb/> favorable. The body of the Jews here <del>were</del> are of Polish <del>rite</del> origin and<lb/> habits and <add>&#63;</add> followed the clothing trade&#44; which <del>was</del> is little calcu&#45;<lb/>lated to gain the esteem of our fellow citizens&#59; but even<lb/> many Jews were unwilling to join them <del>for</del> on account of their <sic>intollerance</sic> and <del>high</del><lb/> emotions at every opportunity. The result is that a kind of stag&#45;<lb/>nation prevails in our community and while <placeName>St Louis</placeName> has become in<lb/> the last <del>decenium</del> ten years one of the largest and wealthiest cities of the<lb/> <placeName>U. S.</placeName> and whilst the number and wealth of its Israelites did<lb/> <del>not remain behind its growth</del> kept pace in proportion&#44; our religious institutions are<lb/> insignificant&#44; our house of worship poor&#44; &#38; there is no learned<lb/> man at the head of the community to devote on the <date>Sabbath</date> our<lb/> minds and hearts&#44; to instruct our children&#44; which are in great<lb/> numbers sent to parochial <del>schools</del> and catholic <del>sisters for getting</del> nunning schools to obtain<lb/> their first <del>instruction</del> rudiments of education. Most probably the old community thought</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>to <del>get</del> obtain adherents by making extravagant charges when a Jew&#44;<lb/> <del>that</del> who was not a member had the sad duty to <add>&#63;</add> to bury his friend<del>s</del><lb/> or relation. This was a <del>rebuke</del> grievance to many and <del>some</del> they formed lately<lb/> though with very little means new congregations&#44; one of which is<lb/> generally called the Bavarian the other the Bohemian <del>Jews</del>. The latter though very few in number <sic>dis<lb/>sing</sic> with themselves by a greater degree of tol<del>l</del>erance&#59; <del>though very few</del><lb/><del>in number</del> they have by great sacrifices purchased a <sic>burring</sic> ground of their<lb/> own and have organized a well <del>organized service</del> regulated system of worship&#44; which is well attended on our<lb/> holy days. It is to be hoped that</p>
			<p><del>May</del> the future furnish a more rejoicing <add>agreeable</add> report <del>in</del> with regard to<lb/> <del>these</del> our interests&#59; until then you will not wonder that<lb/> your <del>journal</del> magazine finds but very few subscribers in this great<lb/> <del>metropolis</del> of the west&#44; and that a <placeName>St Louis</placeName> Paper&#42;&#44; speaking of Jews<lb/> in general and &#40;though as a catholic organ inclined to speak favorably<lb/> of them&#41; mentions the Jews of <placeName>South Carolina</placeName> and <placeName>Savannah</placeName><lb/> of <placeName>New York</placeName> and <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> but does not find anything to say in<lb/> praise of those Jews&#44; that are its own readers.</p>
			<p rend="indent(10)"><persName role="author">I.B.&#40;usch&#41;</persName></p>
			<p>&#42; the St Louis Union of the <date>25th of April</date><lb/> contained the following article&#58;</p>
          
